07907nam a22007935i 9781552388617DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815523886177 a10.1515/97815523886172doi  a(DE-B1597)664048  a(OCoLC)948828474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a303.48/320971qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aMoving Natures :bMobility and the Environment in Canadian History /ced. by Ben Bradley, Jay Young, Colin M. Coates. 1aCalgary, Alberta : bUniversity of Calgary Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b25 b&w and 13 colour illustrations, 9 maps, 2 tables, notes, bibliography, index  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCanadian History and Environment ;v500tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tMoving Natures in Canadian History: An Introduction -- tProduction, Pathways, and Supply -- tMaitland’s Moment: Turning Nova Scotia’s Forests into Ships for the Global Commodity Trade in the Mid-Nineteenth Century -- tForest, Stream and . . . Snowstorms? Seasonality, Nature, and Mobility on the Intercolonial Railway, 1876–1914 -- tSupply Networks in the Age of Steamboat Navigation: Lakeside Mobility in Muskoka, Ontario, 1880–1930 -- tSeasonality and Mobility in Northern Saskatchewan, 1890–1950 -- tCreating the St. Lawrence Seaway: Mobility and a Modern Megaproject -- tSoils and Subways: Excavating Environments during the Building of Rapid Transit in Toronto, 1944–1968 -- tThe Windsor-Detroit Borderland: The Making of a Key North American Environment of Mobility -- tConsumption, Landscape, and Leisure -- tViews from the Deck: Union Steamship Cruises on Canada’s Pacific Coast, 1889–1958 -- tProducing and Consuming Spaces of Sport and Leisure: The Encampments and Regattas of the American Canoe Association, 1880–1903 -- tWhat Was Driving Golf? Mobility, Nature, and the Making of Canadian Leisure Landscapes, 1870–1930 -- tRails, Trails, Roads, and Lodgings: Networks of Mobility and the Touristic Development of the “Canadian Pacific Rockies,” 1885–1930 -- tAutomobile Tourism in Quebec and Ontario: Development, Promotion, and Representations, 1920–1945 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMobility - the movements of people, things, and ideas, as well as their associated cultural meanings - has been a key factor in shaping Canadians' perceptions of and interactions with their country. Approaching the burgeoning field of environmental history in Canada through the lens of mobility reveals some of the distinctive ways in which Canadians have come to terms with the country's climate and landscape. Spanning Canada's diverse regions, throughout its history, from the closing of the age of sail to the contemporary era of just-on-time delivery, Moving Natures: Mobility and the Environment in Canadian History examines a wide range of topics, from the impact of seasonal climactic conditions on different transportation modes, to the environmental consequences of building mobility corridors and pathways, to the relationship between changing forms of mobility with tourism and other recreational activities. Contributors make use of traditional archival sources, as well as historical geographic information systems (HGIS), qualitative and quantitative analysis, and critical theory. This thought-provoking collection divides the intersection of environmental and mobility history into two approaches. The chapters in the first section deal primarily with the construction and productive use of mobility technologies and infrastructure, as well as their environmental constraints and consequences. The chapters in the second section focus on consumers' uses of those vehicles and pathways: on pleasure travel, tourism, and recreational mobility. Together, they highlight three quintessentially Canadian themes: seasonality, links between mobility and natural resource development, and urbanites' experiences of the environment through mobility. With contributions by: Judy Burns Jim Clifford Ken Cruikshank Jessica Dunkin Elizabeth L. Jewett Don Lafreniere Elsa Lam Maude-Emmanuelle Lambert J.I. Little Daniel Macfarlane Merle Massie Tor H. Oiamo Joy Parr Thomas Peace Andrew Watson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory (General). 0aHuman ecology. Anthropogeography. 0aTransportation and communications. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh1 aBradley, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Ben, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurns, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifford, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Colin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Colin M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCruikshank, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunkin, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJewett, Elizabeth L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLafreniere, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLam, Elsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Maude-Emmanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, J. I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, J.I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacfarlane, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela